---

<DocsLayout
  title="System Architecture"
  description="ostk architecture: kernel binary law (10 invariants), the observation substrate, the daemon, the System ABI, write interception, drivers, and the application layer."
  sectionLabel="SECTION_01 // ARCHITECTURE"
  activeTab="architecture"
>
  <p class="font-headline text-lg text-on-surface-variant italic leading-relaxed max-w-xl mb-12">
    A single Rust binary. Five layers from the bottom up: kernel binary law, the observation substrate, the daemon, the System ABI, and drivers — with the application layer on top. Each layer holds a contract the layer above relies on; each contract is mechanically enforceable.
  </p>

  <!-- The Kernel -->
  <section class="mb-16">
    <h2 class="serif-text text-3xl font-medium text-on-surface mb-2">The Kernel — Ten Invariants</h2>
    <p class="font-body text-xs text-secondary mb-6 max-w-xl">
      Statically linked. The kernel's binary contract is a set of invariants every operation upholds — bounded waits, owned state, dead-process reaping, namespace isolation, handle uniqueness. These are not features. They are the load-bearing properties without which composition breaks. Source: <a href="https://github.com/os-tack/haystack/blob/main/docs/spec/llmos-posix-kernel.md" class="text-primary hover:underline"><code>docs/spec/llmos-posix-kernel.md</code></a> v2.4.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-surface-container-low p-6 border-l-2 border-primary mb-8">
      <h3 class="section-label-secondary mb-4">KERNEL_INVARIANTS_I_THROUGH_X</h3>
      <div class="space-y-3">
        {[
          { num: 'I',    name: 'BOUNDED_WAIT',         desc: 'Every blocking call has a deadline. No unbounded waits anywhere — every receive, lock acquisition, syscall has a timeout. Replaces POSIX select(tv).' },
          { num: 'II',   name: 'OWNED_STATE',          desc: 'Every kernel-visible piece of state has exactly one owner with the authority to mutate it. Reads are wide; writes are narrow.' },
          { num: 'III',  name: 'SUBREAPER',            desc: 'Dead processes do not become zombies. The kernel reaps orphaned children on parent exit, exactly as POSIX init does. Implemented by ostk init.' },
          { num: 'IV',   name: 'ROOT_NAMESPACE_ISOLATION', desc: 'Each project boots into an isolated kernel namespace. Tests cannot bleed audit rows into the live project; the live project cannot see test fleet state.' },
          { num: 'V',    name: 'PATH_AND_HANDLE',      desc: 'Every resource has both a stable path AND a kernel-issued handle. Path = how operators address it; handle = how the kernel keeps two callers from colliding.' },
          { num: 'VI',   name: 'PROCESS_IDENTITY_QUAD', desc: 'Every agent has (alias, parent, group, session) — the POSIX (pid, ppid, pgid, sid) quad reproduced at the agent layer.' },
          { num: 'VII',  name: 'SIGNAL_TABLE_CLOSURE', desc: 'Coordination is signals from a numbered table. No ad-hoc string-named events. The signal set is closed and mechanically enumerable.' },
          { num: 'VIII', name: 'ANCHOR_EXCLUSIVITY',   desc: 'Exactly one daemon owns the kernel socket per project. No two anchors race; the second to bind exits. Eliminates the cascade where two daemons fight for state.' },
          { num: 'IX',   name: 'HANDLE_LIFETIME_UNIQUENESS', desc: 'A kernel handle is unique across its lifetime — a freed handle is never reused for a different resource. Stale references fail closed, never mis-match.' },
          { num: 'X',    name: 'CONNECTION_CONTINUITY', desc: 'A client whose socket drops can re-attach without losing audit lineage. Sessions outlive transports.' },
        ].map(inv => (
          <div class="grid grid-cols-12 gap-4 text-xs font-body py-2 border-b border-surface-variant">
            <span class="col-span-1 serif-text text-primary font-bold">{inv.num}</span>
            <span class="col-span-3 text-primary">{inv.name}</span>
            <span class="col-span-8 text-secondary">{inv.desc}</span>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>
      <p class="font-body text-[10px] text-outline mt-4">
        Candidate Invariant XI — CPU Output Durability — pending panel ratification (→1628). Full normative text and proof sketches: <code class="text-primary">docs/spec/llmos-posix-kernel.md</code>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- The Observation Substrate -->
  <section class="mb-16">
    <h2 class="serif-text text-3xl font-medium text-on-surface mb-2">The Observation Substrate</h2>
    <p class="font-body text-xs text-secondary mb-6 max-w-xl">
      Above the kernel sits the substrate that makes its state queryable. ostk's audit ring (<code class="text-primary">.ostk/journal.jsonl</code>) is the system's write-ahead log; the observation substrate projects it onto a VFS namespace agents and operators can read directly. Source: <a href="https://github.com/os-tack/haystack/blob/main/docs/spec/llmos-observation-substrate.md" class="text-primary hover:underline"><code>docs/spec/llmos-observation-substrate.md</code></a>.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-surface-container-low p-6 mb-6 max-w-3xl">
      <p class="font-body text-xs text-secondary mb-4 italic">
        Analogy: Postgres logical decoding. The kernel writes the WAL; subscribers tap it; the rest of the system queries the projections.
      </p>
      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-px bg-surface-variant">
        {[
          { label: 'WAL', desc: '.ostk/journal.jsonl — append-only, single-writer, hash-chained, Ed25519-signed in-process.' },
          { label: 'LOGICAL_SLOT', desc: 'Each Indexer subscriber registration in dispatch::fire — taps the audit ring, never blocks the writer.' },
          { label: 'DECODED_ROWS', desc: 'Vec<GraphOp> returned by on_audit — derived facts the substrate exposes.' },
          { label: 'OUTPUT_VIEWS', desc: '.ostk/index/graph.edges.<class>.jsonl shard files — the queried surface.' },
          { label: 'GEN_TABLE', desc: '.ostk/gen_table.jsonl — per-file generation counters, the OCC anchor for invisible-write tracking.' },
          { label: 'REGISTRIES', desc: 'kernel::registry boundary (forthcoming, EPIC →1652) — typed read API for substrate consumers; cache + indexer become its private impl.' },
        ].map(row => (
          <div class="bg-surface-container p-4">
            <div class="font-label text-[10px] text-primary mb-1">{row.label}</div>
            <div class="font-body text-xs text-secondary">{row.desc}</div>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>

    <p class="font-body text-xs text-secondary max-w-xl">
      Why this matters: agents and operators query a single derived view through a stable path. No polling, no replication, no separate truth source. Lose the daemon and the registries rebuild from journal replay; lose the registries and the kernel keeps writing. <span class="text-primary">→</span> <a href="/docs/needles" class="text-primary hover:underline">NEEDLES</a> for the cross-session memory built on top.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- The Daemon -->
  <section class="mb-16">
    <h2 class="serif-text text-3xl font-medium text-on-surface mb-2">The Daemon</h2>
    <p class="font-body text-xs text-secondary mb-6 max-w-xl">
      <code class="text-primary">ostk daemon</code> starts the kernel daemon — a long-lived anchor process holding the socket, the in-memory process table, the scheduler, and the substrate registries. <code class="text-primary">ostk listen</code> is a legacy alias for the same verb.
    </p>

    <div class="grid grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-8">
      {[
        { title: 'SESSION_MGMT', desc: 'Agents run as managed sessions. Each carries identity, heartbeat, drain snapshot. See SESSION_TOPOLOGY.' },
        { title: 'SCHEDULER_TICK', desc: 'Background task wakes the scheduler on a deadline (Invariant I). Inspects fleet state, dispatches work, reaps dead sessions (III).' },
        { title: 'CRASH_RECOVERY', desc: 'Drain snapshots at every turn boundary. On daemon restart, fold(journal.jsonl) reconstructs fleet and rehydrates sessions.' },
        { title: 'CLIENT_MULTIPLEX', desc: 'TUI, MCP clients, CLI one-shots, and IDE extensions attach/detach via the kernel socket. Sessions persist across client disconnects (X).' },
      ].map(card => (
        <div class="bg-surface-container p-6">
          <h3 class="font-body text-sm text-primary font-bold mb-2">{card.title}</h3>
          <p class="font-body text-xs text-secondary">{card.desc}</p>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>

    <p class="font-body text-xs text-secondary max-w-xl">
      The daemon is a cache, not a ledger. Source of truth is the journal + gen_table + drain snapshots on disk. <code class="text-primary">ostk daemon restart</code> swaps a rebuilt binary cleanly without losing audit lineage. <span class="text-primary">→</span> <a href="/docs/session-topology" class="text-primary hover:underline">SESSION_TOPOLOGY</a>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- The System ABI -->
  <section class="mb-16">
    <h2 class="serif-text text-3xl font-medium text-on-surface mb-2">The System ABI</h2>
    <p class="font-body text-xs text-secondary mb-6 max-w-xl">
      The kernel's syscall surface for agents. A versioned, schema'd set of verbs — currently 27 — that any LLM-driven process can call to read or mutate substrate state. Source of truth: <code class="text-primary">KERNEL_ABI_VERBS</code> in <code class="text-primary">src/kernel/isa/mod.rs</code>. EPIC →1589.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-surface-container-low p-6 border-l-2 border-primary mb-6 max-w-3xl">
      <h3 class="section-label-secondary mb-4">ABI_INTROSPECTION</h3>
      <div class="space-y-2 font-body text-xs">
        <div class="flex gap-4">
          <code class="text-primary w-48 shrink-0">ostk abi list</code>
          <span class="text-secondary">Enumerate every System ABI verb with tier + signature.</span>
        </div>
        <div class="flex gap-4">
          <code class="text-primary w-48 shrink-0">ostk abi show &lt;verb&gt;</code>
          <span class="text-secondary">Render the full schema for one verb — args, return shape, semantics.</span>
        </div>
        <div class="flex gap-4">
          <code class="text-primary w-48 shrink-0">ostk abi version</code>
          <span class="text-secondary">Print the ABI version + sha256 hash. Today: v1.0.0.</span>
        </div>
        <div class="flex gap-4">
          <code class="text-primary w-48 shrink-0">ostk abi diff &lt;ref&gt;</code>
          <span class="text-secondary">Diff the current ABI against a git ref. Detects breaking changes.</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p class="font-body text-xs text-secondary max-w-xl">
      The ABI separates the agent-callable surface (stable, schema'd) from the operator-facing CLI (free to evolve). MCP clients reach the kernel through this ABI via the <a href="/docs/mcp" class="text-primary hover:underline">MCP bridge</a>. Verb names that begin with <code class="text-primary">_</code> (e.g. <code class="text-primary">_agent</code>) are kernel-internal primitives, hidden from <code class="text-primary">ostk --help</code>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Write Interception -->
  <section class="mb-16">
    <h2 class="serif-text text-3xl font-medium text-on-surface mb-2">Write Interception</h2>
    <div class="bg-surface-container-high p-6 border-t-4 border-primary mb-6">
      <p class="font-body text-xs text-on-surface mb-4">
        Default: ostk intercepts at the <span class="text-primary font-bold">tool layer</span>. Agents call kernel primitives (<code class="text-primary">fs_ops</code>, <code class="text-primary">read</code>, <code class="text-primary">bash</code>) that apply policy, gen_table tracking, and pin caps before bytes hit disk. No LD_PRELOAD, no ptrace, no kqueue observer.
      </p>
      <p class="font-body text-xs text-secondary mb-4">
        Tool-layer interception has one honest limitation: an agent that escapes the tool path — by invoking a shell that writes directly — bypasses the kernel for that write. Three layers of defense:
      </p>
      <ol class="font-body text-xs text-secondary list-decimal pl-5 space-y-2 mb-4">
        <li><span class="text-primary font-bold">Process sandbox (always on).</span> The <code class="text-primary">nono</code> subsystem enforces filesystem restrictions at the OS layer — Landlock on Linux, Seatbelt on macOS. Agents physically cannot write outside their allowed paths. <code class="text-primary">src/kernel/sandbox.rs</code>.</li>
        <li><span class="text-primary font-bold">FUSE auto-mount (optional).</span> The daemon-managed FUSE mount mirrors the project tree and logs every write op through the kernel. Configurable via HUMANFILE preferences. EPIC →1641, <code class="text-primary">src/fuse/passthrough.rs</code>, <code class="text-primary">src/kernel/vfs/lifecycle.rs</code>.</li>
        <li><span class="text-primary font-bold">Bypass detection.</span> Files modified outside the kernel surface are flagged on next read with a <code class="text-primary">[bypass]</code> envelope. Visibility, not enforcement — but loud.</li>
      </ol>
      <p class="font-body text-xs text-secondary">
        Tool-layer covers the expected path; the OS sandbox covers the escape path; FUSE is the observability upgrade for operators who want every byte logged regardless of how it got written. No single layer is load-bearing on its own.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- FCP Drivers -->
  <section class="mb-16">
    <h2 class="serif-text text-3xl font-medium text-on-surface mb-2">FCP Drivers</h2>
    <p class="font-body text-xs text-secondary mb-6 max-w-xl">
      Drivers extend the kernel with domain capabilities via the File Context Protocol — MCP servers that let agents interact with complex file formats through a verb-based DSL. The kernel proxies them via <code class="text-primary">ostk driver</code> (formerly <code class="text-primary">ostk mcp</code>); see <a href="/docs/mcp" class="text-primary hover:underline">MCP</a> §Direction 02.
    </p>

    <div class="mb-8">
      <h3 class="section-label-secondary mb-4">INTERNAL_DRIVERS</h3>
      <div class="bg-surface-container-low p-6">
        <div class="space-y-3">
          {[
            { name: 'fcp-screen', caps: '[tty]', desc: 'TUI rendering — fleet status, work queue, permission modals.' },
            { name: 'fcp-web', caps: '[]', desc: 'Web page reading — fetch, render, extract content from URLs.' },
            { name: 'fcp-llm', caps: '[]', desc: 'LLM inference — CpuDriver trait, provider routing (Anthropic, Gemini, Mistral, OpenRouter, ollama, mlx, apple-olleh).' },
            { name: 'fcp-recall', caps: '[]', desc: 'Cross-project recall over decisions + needles + transcripts.' },
            { name: 'fcp-olleh', caps: '[]', desc: 'Apple-Silicon-resident inference via the olleh server (port 11941).' },
          ].map(driver => (
            <div class="flex gap-6 text-xs font-body py-2 border-b border-surface-variant">
              <span class="text-primary w-32 shrink-0">{driver.name}</span>
              <span class="text-outline w-16 shrink-0">{driver.caps}</span>
              <span class="text-secondary">{driver.desc}</span>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div>
      <h3 class="section-label-secondary mb-4">EXTERNAL_DRIVERS</h3>
      <div class="bg-surface-container-low p-6">
        <div class="space-y-3">
          {[
            { name: 'fcp-rust', desc: 'Rust analysis via rust-analyzer — crate graph, type resolution, diagnostics.', repo: 'os-tack/fcp-rust' },
            { name: 'fcp-python', desc: 'Python intelligence via pylsp — query and refactor Python codebases.', repo: 'os-tack/fcp-python' },
            { name: 'fcp-drawio', desc: 'Create and edit draw.io diagrams through intent-level commands.', repo: 'os-tack/fcp-drawio' },
            { name: 'fcp-pdf', desc: 'Semantic PDF operations — extract, search, manipulate PDF content.', repo: 'os-tack/fcp-pdf' },
            { name: 'fcp-sheets', desc: 'Semantic spreadsheet operations — query and edit cells, formulas, ranges.', repo: 'os-tack/fcp-sheets' },
            { name: 'fcp-slides', desc: 'Slide deck operations for presentation file formats.', repo: 'os-tack/fcp-slides' },
            { name: 'fcp-midi', desc: 'Semantic MIDI music composition — notes, tracks, instruments.', repo: 'os-tack/fcp-midi' },
            { name: 'fcp-regex', desc: 'Regex construction via named fragment composition.', repo: 'os-tack/fcp-regex' },
            { name: 'fcp-terraform', desc: 'Terraform HCL generation — modules, resources, variables.', repo: 'os-tack/fcp-terraform' },
          ].map(driver => (
            <div class="flex gap-6 text-xs font-body py-2 border-b border-surface-variant">
              <span class="text-primary w-32 shrink-0">{driver.name}</span>
              <span class="text-secondary flex-1">{driver.desc}</span>
              <a href={`https://github.com/${driver.repo}`} class="text-primary hover:underline shrink-0">{driver.repo}</a>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-8">
      <h3 class="section-label-secondary mb-4">FRAMEWORK</h3>
      <div class="bg-surface-container-low p-6">
        <div class="space-y-3">
          {[
            { name: 'fcp', desc: 'File Context Protocol specification — verb-based DSL for file operations.', repo: 'os-tack/fcp' },
            { name: 'fcp-core', desc: 'Shared framework for building FCP servers (TypeScript + Python).', repo: 'os-tack/fcp-core' },
            { name: 'fcp-core-rust', desc: 'Shared Rust framework for building FCP servers.', repo: 'os-tack/fcp-core-rust' },
          ].map(driver => (
            <div class="flex gap-6 text-xs font-body py-2 border-b border-surface-variant">
              <span class="text-primary w-32 shrink-0">{driver.name}</span>
              <span class="text-secondary flex-1">{driver.desc}</span>
              <a href={`https://github.com/${driver.repo}`} class="text-primary hover:underline shrink-0">{driver.repo}</a>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- The Application Layer -->
  <section class="mb-16">
    <h2 class="serif-text text-3xl font-medium text-on-surface mb-2">The Application Layer</h2>
    <p class="font-body text-xs text-secondary mb-4 max-w-xl">
      Above the daemon, the System ABI, and the drivers sits the application layer — the unit of work an operator hands to the substrate. <code class="text-primary">application/v1</code> defines a content-addressed, signed directory tree with declared capabilities, supervisor trees, and a claim-graph lifecycle. Source: <a href="https://github.com/os-tack/haystack/blob/main/docs/spec/llmos-application.md" class="text-primary hover:underline"><code>docs/spec/llmos-application.md</code></a> v0.1 RATIFIED.
    </p>
    <p class="font-body text-xs text-outline italic max-w-xl mb-4">
      "I can hand you my application as a signed file. You install it. You start it. It runs. When it finishes, I can verify what happened against the audit chain you publish." — application/v1 §1
    </p>
    <p class="font-body text-xs text-secondary max-w-xl">
      Lifecycle verbs (<code class="text-primary">ostk app install / start / stop / upgrade / uninstall</code>) emit nine ratified claim schemas riding <code class="text-primary">EventKind::Claim</code>. The application's runtime existence IS its claim graph slice keyed by <code class="text-primary">(app_id, install_id, start_id)</code>.
    </p>
  </section>

